The nursery school is also part of offices that included architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint of Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
Arch. Design, a project-architectonic company whose workshops produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini-maternal business school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially the age of children, and it was important that women architects and project leaders should be able to return to work quickly.
Along with reduced time contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by Arch. Design as part of its social program.
Manufacturers and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work taking care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-maternal school is financed through the European Social Fund through the operational programme of human resources and the State budget of the Czech Republic.
They were able to purchase equipment and appliances and, after two years, to provide qualified personnel and start-up.
After using the funding endowment (two years) Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and it was the Economy rating company that helped to make the staffing request.
Care for children is provided by qualified staff, throughout the day a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of children. Children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they are over three years old for most.
Since it is a "mini-maternal school" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although individual care and education are used, the programme of the minima nursery school is comparable to that of pre-school education.
Children don't just play there, but quality education is also provided - from the beginning to preparation for school benches English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and do not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children in a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
No wonder there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and who are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The house in bone still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi's interiors.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received the nickname House in bone from the premises.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the New Art of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation one sees the geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the windows frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyepiece and the lamelles.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district on the Passeig de Gracia street at number 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a house with multiple dwellings was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the façade were born.
For the façade have also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and Guell Park where there are other Gaudi works.
The locals nicknamed the house hot just after its finish because of its organic forms "the House in bone".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of construction sculpture contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation of Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the directives for the construction of those days and did not let themselves be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained a permit from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the municipal council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, the members of the municipal council did not like the construction pillars to be built on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented from a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which you access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the lounges and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi reconstruction received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with the wells of lights.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough simply to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which instead absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits as they found that it was a lucrative company and expanded the scope of visits to common spaces and attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tour card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other buildings of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you need to quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
