Tracking devices are increasingly being requested by parents who want to watch their children.
Fear for their child is causing more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can be used just as well to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as by example that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disrupt their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about espionage but only about another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company MAcro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know what "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to carry something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control.'
"Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything in his power to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as tracking devices develop, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who provides tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on regular issue after a specified period of time".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
'The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in an elongated position without moving," Cech says.
According to him the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special prologiciel.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn in pendants the size of a matchbox or to smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil company, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the possible aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
This is a combination of a position acquisition system using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
