At the Lands Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public competition
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives passed the handcuffs to the local contractor and real estate dealer Lubos. G.
He had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a restitution request in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific candidate.
He was supposed to pay Lubos G. half a million kroner.
"For the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for an insider's offence as part of a call for tenders and a public competition," said Pravo newspaper the head of Plzen Antonie Zelena's Public Prosecutor's Office, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
The police released this 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
In order to know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in view of so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, the spokesman for the Lubomira Cerna Land Fund said that the police had actually arrested Plzen in a separate workplace during the public competition.
"He was a client and under no circumstances an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Appeal to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Law" and is put in place when several legal candidates manifest themselves.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to restitution which must be settled before the value of the land is announced."
"According to the proposed rights a ranking of the buyers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights," the Fund spokesman explained.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and since he himself was also a beneficiary because he had purchased a large number of rights to restitution, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in by retiring.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Founds of the Lands).
He was involved in the case of the former head of FdT Vaclav Sankot, who was prosecuted for publishing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been published.
Precisely Lubos G. had obtained, for example, land for the construction of public communications, concretely in place and place where the access artery to the industrial zone of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept it because otherwise it would put the construction in jeopardy by blocking the land.
