Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The Department of Justice prosecutors have lifted the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case involving an assistant in an old campaign and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the wife's husband, announced the Senator's lawyers on Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican of Nevada who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made the big national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this issue.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice that there would be significant evidence that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as treasurer during a campaign in Ensign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for a year by law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends prior to the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called lobbying gate ban.
According to evidence made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantially violate the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks by its Public Integrity Section, including last year's decisions to drop the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens accused of lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Chief Executive Officer of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government official can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Mr. Ensign's Senior Counsel, Paul Coggins, stated in an interview that he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice on Monday and a follow-up the following day, telling him that the Department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed on Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's Hampton parents violated the federal election law.
The Electoral Commission stated that it did not have enough evidence to prove that money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, an important Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
