This paved the way for an agreement on Wednesday to eliminate the remaining £500, according to an official who referred to the condition of anonymity due to the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit, organized at the initiative of Obama, where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was beneficial to provide an invitation to the former Soviet Republic following the summit in 2012.
"I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit Nuclear Security Summit."
"This proves to me that this process works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Global Security Partnership, a nuclear security promotion group.
Clinton described the agreement as a "very significant, important step" by Belarus.
Obama committed to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials around the world in the next four years.
