It seems that President Zapatero also heard it in this form and its double declaration (the reforms promised after the meeting last Saturday with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticisms, we have opened the way to the thesis that we must put order at home.
But the red line Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to move it.
And among the possibilities we are considering, we cannot rule out abandoning a monetary zone that is too crowded with countries that are not serious.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that she had warned us.
Sport and fraud of the law
The ruses similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The urdious expulsion in principle by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match of 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink to flow on the anti-sport character of such behavior and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the game ended (which their team was already clearly winning), the two players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, the two players will fulfill the regulatory sanction during the next game of the barrage match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards in the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned with two games the team coach, José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this one or similar is not a new practice, if not rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions has sentenced its players to a fine for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds another episode to its dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether such actions involve the commission of a fraud of law, because they are actions which are respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the assets that understands the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with the right game is to prevent the offending players' team from taking unfair advantage of the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not conform to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules has not been carried out in hiding to try to avoid the sanction, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders get from the intentional mistakes examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that you do not put yourself in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and you do not get an advantage in the same game either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course, the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminateness, because the team could be eliminated all at once and apart from that, with this action the players perform a penalty game and pass to the second cycle of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladders, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote profit to the maximum of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the time at which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without losing the penalty or running away from it.
Although the border between genius and law enforcement fraud is widespread, on this occasion I think we've had a clear case of genius.
It seems to me that the controversy arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director transmits to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
