The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
Persons must go to Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to interviewing the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the US Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (CSA) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not be required to present themselves to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will present themselves only to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
