Avenger hackers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only bring back what could have been read in any newspaper for months (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Khadafi's sinister caricature profile had long been for the artists of sketch material cabaret.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that every book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (or know where to look for news about the incessant), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and which reconfirms what they have already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (if not he could be, what do I know, editor at Liberation), who retain as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the previous week.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call themselves or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become centres of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows that very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put both the victims and the "bulls" in crisis.
But let's come to the deep nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that knowing about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means removing all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too great for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any reserved information - this would mean publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is hopeless to be able to maintain confidential reports by telephone.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine agents of the government who move discreetly in due diligence to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: in the background, the attempt to spy on the Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in crabs, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph (telephone).
Videocassettes (analogs) had allowed cinema researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and back and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not extraordinary, therefore, that communication policy and techniques should return to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
It is now the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France stifles its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly released financing (such fast start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French trinkets are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU came out with the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency exercise was appreciable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced €2.2 billion, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France believes that the financing of "all new projects" for 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses its method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ loaned is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, it should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% of loans (€388.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its commitment, France spends only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice pass round!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she can make it appear that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy that has carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that the UNFCCC is.
Let us hope that will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): there will be no escape from the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
